WEBVTT

00:20.280 --> 00:22.300
PIECES OF EIGHT

00:23.280 --> 00:28.500
Owing to the count of the vessel, the masts hung far out over the water, and from my perch

00:28.500 --> 00:32.940
on the cross-trees I had nothing below me but the surface of the bay. Hans, who was

00:32.940 --> 00:37.800
not so far up, was in consequence nearer to the ship, and fell between me and the bulwarks.

00:38.440 --> 00:43.660
He rose once to the surface in a lather of foam and blood, and then sank again for good.

00:45.700 --> 00:50.040
As the water settled, I could see him lying huddled together on the clean, bright sand

00:50.040 --> 00:55.840
in the shadow of the vessel's sides. A fish or two whipped past his body. Sometimes by

00:55.840 --> 00:59.840
the quivering of the water he appeared to move a little, as if he were trying to rise.

01:01.660 --> 01:06.720
But he was dead enough for all that, being both shot and drowned, and was food for fish

01:06.720 --> 01:09.480
in the very place where he had designed my slaughter.

01:11.340 --> 01:17.240
I was no sooner certain of this than I began to feel sick, faint, and terrified. The hot

01:17.240 --> 01:21.620
blood was running over my back and chest. The dirk where it had pinned my shoulder to

01:21.620 --> 01:27.660
like a hot iron. Yet it was not so much these real sufferings that distressed me. For these

01:27.660 --> 01:32.640
it seemed to me I could bear without a murmur. It was the horror I had upon my mind of falling

01:32.640 --> 01:37.080
from the cross-trees into that still green water beside the body of the coxswain.

01:38.620 --> 01:43.820
I clung with both hands until my nails ached, and I shut my eyes as if to cover up the peril.

01:44.660 --> 01:49.820
Gradually my mind came back again, my pulses quieted down to a more natural time, and I

01:49.820 --> 01:51.700
was once again in possession of myself.

01:52.980 --> 01:57.680
It was my first thought to pluck forth the dirk, but either it stuck too hard or my nerve

01:57.680 --> 02:03.000
failed me, and I desisted with a violent shudder. Oddly enough that very shudder did the business.

02:03.440 --> 02:07.440
The knife, in fact, had come the nearest in the world to missing me altogether. It held

02:07.440 --> 02:13.000
me by a mere pinch of skin, and this the shudder tore away. The blood ran down the faster,

02:13.060 --> 02:17.580
to be sure, but I was my own master again, and only tacked to the mast by my coat and

02:18.940 --> 02:23.460
These last I broke through with a sudden jerk, and then regained the deck by the starboard

02:24.040 --> 02:28.380
shrouds, for nothing in the world would I have again ventured, shaken as I was, upon

02:28.380 --> 02:31.420
the overhanging port shrouds from which Israel had so lately fallen.

02:32.840 --> 02:37.980
I went below and did what I could for my wound. It pained me a good deal and still bled freely,

02:38.420 --> 02:42.620
but it was neither deep nor dangerous, nor did it greatly gall me when I used my arm.

02:43.280 --> 02:47.920
Then I looked around me, and as the ship was now, in a sense, my own, I began to think

02:47.920 --> 02:53.880
of clearing it from its last passenger, the dead man O'Brien. He had pitched, as I have

02:53.880 --> 02:59.480
said, against the bulwarks, where he lay like some horrible ungainly sort of puppet, life-size

02:59.480 --> 03:05.260
indeed, but how different from life's colour or life's comeliness. In that position I could

03:05.260 --> 03:09.760
easily have my way with him, and as the habit of tragical adventures had worn off almost

03:09.760 --> 03:13.860
all my terror for the dead, I took him by the waist as if he had been a sack of bran,

03:13.980 --> 03:19.140
and with one good heave tumbled him overboard. He went in with a sounding plunge, the red

03:19.140 --> 03:23.240
cap came off and remained floating on the surface, and as soon as the splash subsided

03:23.240 --> 03:28.040
I could see him and Israel lying side by side, both wavering with the tremulous movement

03:28.040 --> 03:34.160
of the water. O'Brien, though still quite a young man, was very bold. There he lay with

03:34.160 --> 03:38.080
that bold head across the knees of the man who had killed him, and the quick fishes steering

03:38.080 --> 03:46.360
to and fro over both. I was now alone upon the ship. The tide had just turned. The sun

03:46.360 --> 03:50.240
was within so few degrees of setting that already the shadow of the pines upon the western

03:50.240 --> 03:55.920
shore began to reach right across the anchorage and fall in patterns on the deck. The evening

03:55.920 --> 03:59.960
breeze had sprung up, and though it was well warded off by the hill with the two peaks

03:59.960 --> 04:04.920
upon the east, the cordage had begun to sing a little softly to itself, and the idle sails

04:04.920 --> 04:12.480
a rattle to and fro. I began to see a danger to the ship. The jibs I speedily doused and

04:12.480 --> 04:17.300
brought tumbling to the deck, but the mainsail was a harder matter. Of course when the schooner

04:17.300 --> 04:21.680
canted over the boom had a swing outboard, and the cap of it and a foot or two of sail

04:21.680 --> 04:26.420
hung even under the water. I thought this made it still more dangerous, yet the strain

04:26.420 --> 04:31.780
was so heavy that I half feared to meddle. At last I got my knife and cut the halyards.

04:32.180 --> 04:36.480
The peak dropped instantly, a great belly of loose canvas floated broad upon the water,

04:36.880 --> 04:41.680
and since, pull as I liked, I could not budge the down-haul, that was the extent of what

04:41.680 --> 04:49.280
I could accomplish. For the rest, the Hispaniola must trust a luck like myself. By this time

04:49.280 --> 04:53.600
the whole anchorage had fallen into shadow, the last rays I remember falling through a

04:53.600 --> 04:58.200
glade of the wood and shining bright as jewels on the flowery mantle of the wreck. It began

04:58.200 --> 05:02.940
to be chill, the tide was rapidly fleeting sea-wood, the schooner settling more and

05:02.940 --> 05:08.500
more on her beam ends. I scrambled forward and looked over. It seemed shallow enough,

05:08.780 --> 05:13.680
and holding the cut-houser in both hands for last security, I let myself drop softly overboard.

05:14.520 --> 05:19.220
The water scarcely reached my waist, the sand was firm and covered with ripple marks, and

05:19.220 --> 05:24.100
I waded ashore in great spirits, leaving the Hispaniola on her side, with her mainsail

05:24.100 --> 05:29.180
trailing wide upon the surface of the bay. About the same time, the sun went fairly down

05:29.180 --> 05:34.460
and the breeze whistled low in the dusk among the tossing pines. At least and at last I

05:34.460 --> 05:39.760
was off the sea, nor had I returned thence empty-handed. There lay the schooner, clear

05:39.760 --> 05:44.200
at last from buccaneers and ready for our own men to board and get to sea again. I had

05:44.200 --> 05:47.680
nothing nearer my fancy than to get home to the stockade and boast of my achievements.

05:48.720 --> 05:53.040
Possibly I might be blamed a bit for my truantry, but the recapture of the Hispaniola was a

05:53.040 --> 05:57.720
wrenching answer, and I hoped that even Captain Smollett would confess I had not lost my time.

05:58.820 --> 06:03.000
So thinking, and in famous spirits, I began to set my face homeward for the blockhouse

06:03.000 --> 06:08.320
and my companions. I remembered that the most easterly of the rivers which drain into Captain

06:08.320 --> 06:12.480
Kidd's anchorage ran from the two-peaked hill upon my left, and I bent my course in

06:12.480 --> 06:17.240
that direction that I might pass the stream whilst it was small. The wood was pretty open,

06:17.460 --> 06:21.460
and keeping along the lower spurs, I had soon turned the corner of that hill, and was not

06:21.460 --> 06:26.740
long after waded to the mid-garve across the water-course. This brought me near to

06:26.740 --> 06:31.560
where I had encountered Ben Gunn, the maroon, and I walked more circumspectly, keeping an

06:31.560 --> 06:36.740
eye on every side. The dusk had come nigh-hand completely, and as I opened out the cleft

06:36.740 --> 06:41.860
between the two peaks, I became aware of a wavering glow against the sky, where, as I

06:41.860 --> 06:46.580
judged, the man of the island was cooking his supper before a roaring fire, and yet

06:46.580 --> 06:50.760
I wondered in my heart that he should show himself so careless, for if I could see this

06:50.760 --> 06:54.440
radiance, might it not reach the eyes of Silver himself, where he camped upon the shore

06:54.440 --> 06:55.420
among the marshes?

06:56.800 --> 07:01.200
Gradually the night fell blacker. It was all I could do to guide myself even roughly towards

07:01.200 --> 07:05.900
my destination. The double hill behind me and the spy-glass on my right hand loomed

07:05.900 --> 07:10.840
faint and fainter. The stars were few and pale, and in the low ground where I wandered,

07:11.000 --> 07:16.280
I kept tripping among bushes and rolling into sandy pits. Suddenly a kind of brightness

07:16.280 --> 07:21.780
fell about me. I looked up. A pale glimmer of moonbeams had alighted on the summit of

07:21.780 --> 07:26.400
the spy-glass, and soon after I saw something broad and silvery moving low down behind the

07:26.400 --> 07:32.400
trees, and knew that the moon had risen. With this to help me, I passed rapidly over what

07:32.400 --> 07:37.080
remained to me of my journey, and sometimes walking, sometimes running, impatiently drew

07:37.080 --> 07:42.800
near to the stockade. Yet as I began to thread the grove that lies before it, I was not so

07:42.800 --> 07:47.040
thoughtless but that I slacked my pace and went a trifle warily. It would have been a

07:47.040 --> 07:50.260
poor end of my adventures to get shot down by my own party and mistake.

07:51.940 --> 07:56.400
The moon was climbing higher and higher. Its light began to fall here and there in masses

07:56.400 --> 08:00.500
through the more open districts of the wood, and right in front of me a glow of a different

08:00.500 --> 08:05.420
colour appeared among the trees. It was red and hot, and now and again it was a little

08:05.420 --> 08:08.740
darkened, as it were the embers of a bonfire smouldering.

08:10.260 --> 08:13.640
For the life of me, I could not think what it might be.

08:15.260 --> 08:20.100
At last I came right down upon the borders of the clearing. The western end was already

08:20.100 --> 08:25.380
steeped in moonshine. The rest, and the block-house itself, still lay in a black shadow checkered

08:25.380 --> 08:30.260
with long silvery streaks of light. On the other side of the house an immense fire had

08:30.260 --> 08:35.160
burned itself into clear embers and shed a steady red reverberation contrasted strongly

08:35.160 --> 08:40.420
with the mellow paleness of the moon. There was not a soul stirring, nor a sound beside

08:40.420 --> 08:41.480
the noises of the breeze.

08:43.320 --> 08:48.960
I stopped, with much wonder in my heart, and perhaps a little terror also. It had not been

08:48.960 --> 08:54.040
our way to build great fires. We were, indeed by the captain's orders, somewhat niggardly

08:54.040 --> 08:57.800
of firewood, and I began to fear that something had gone wrong while I was absent.

08:58.960 --> 09:03.620
I stole round by the eastern end, keeping close in shadow, and at a convenient place

09:03.620 --> 09:06.220
where the darkness was thickest, crossed the palisade.

09:07.960 --> 09:12.500
To make assurance to Shura, I got upon my knees and hands and crawled without a sound

09:12.500 --> 09:17.580
towards the corner of the house. As I drew nearer, my heart was suddenly and greatly

09:17.580 --> 09:22.040
lightened. It is not a pleasant noise in itself, and I have often complained of it at other

09:22.040 --> 09:26.680
times, but just then it was like music to hear my friends snoring together so loud and

09:26.680 --> 09:32.280
peaceful in their sleep. The sea-cry of the watch, that beautiful all's well, never fell

09:32.280 --> 09:33.960
more reassuringly on my ear.

09:36.200 --> 09:40.640
In the meantime, there was no doubt of one thing. They had kept an infamous bad watch.

09:41.160 --> 09:44.620
If it had been Silver and his lads that were now creeping in on them, not a soul would

09:44.620 --> 09:48.940
have seen daybreak. That was what it was, thought I, to have had the captain wounded,

09:49.380 --> 09:53.520
and again I blamed myself sharply for leaving them in that danger with so few to mount guard.

09:56.320 --> 10:01.960
By this time I had got to the door and stood up. All was dark within, so that I could distinguish

10:01.960 --> 10:07.160
nothing by the eye. As for sounds, there was the steady drone of the snorers and a small

10:07.160 --> 10:11.520
occasional noise, a flickering or pecking that I could in no way account for.

10:13.320 --> 10:18.380
With my arms before me, I walked steadily in. I should lie down in my own place, I thought

10:18.380 --> 10:21.840
with a silent chuckle, and enjoy their faces when they found me in the morning.

10:23.540 --> 10:29.120
My foot struck something yielding. It was a sleeper's leg, and he turned and groaned

10:29.120 --> 10:35.720
without awaking. And then all of a sudden a shrill voice broke forth out of the darkness.

10:36.240 --> 10:40.860
—Pieces of eight! Pieces of eight! Pieces of eight! Pieces of eight! Pieces of eight!

10:41.300 --> 10:44.700
And so forth, without pause or change, like the clacking of a tiny mill.

10:45.480 --> 10:50.380
Silver's green parrot, Captain Flint. It was she whom I had heard pecking at a piece of

10:50.380 --> 10:54.940
bark. It was she keeping better watch than any human being, who thus announced my arrival

10:54.940 --> 11:00.580
with her wearisome refrain. I had no time left to me to recover. At the sharp clipping

11:00.580 --> 11:04.880
tone of the parrot, the sleepers awoke and sprang up, and with a mighty oath the voice

11:04.880 --> 11:11.260
of Silver cried, Who goes? I turned to run, struck violently against one person, recoiled

11:11.260 --> 11:15.600
and ran full into the arms of a second, who for his part closed upon and held me tight.

11:16.300 --> 11:19.380
—Bring a torch, Dick! said Silver when my capture was thus assured.

11:19.380 --> 11:24.680
And one of the men left the log-house, and presently returned with a lighted brand.

